"""
MKT Christ Layer — Jeremiah chapters 7–9
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-jeremiah-7-9-fill.py

Ch 7: Temple Sermon — the most Christologically dense chapter of the three.
Ch 8: Balm in Gilead / the physician oracle.
Ch 9: Weeping prophet / boasting in the Lord.

Key Christological pivots:
- 7:11: 'den of robbers' — Jesus quotes this in all three Synoptics at the temple
  cleansing, claiming the temple sermon's authority for his own action.
- 7:25-26: 'servants the prophets' rejected — the Parable of the Tenants pattern
  (Matt 21:33-46): servants sent → rejected → son sent → killed.
- 7:31-32: Topheth/Gehenna — Jesus's primary image of eschatological judgment;
  Gehenna (valley of Ben Hinnom) derives from 7:31's 'Valley of Ben Hinnom'.
- 8:22: 'No balm in Gilead? No physician?' — Jesus as the divine physician
  (Matt 9:12; Mark 2:17) fulfills this lament: he IS the balm and the physician.
- 9:1: Weeping prophet — Jesus weeps over Jerusalem (Luke 19:41-44) in explicit
  fulfilment of Jeremiah's own weeping; the prophet's grief becomes the Son's grief.
- 9:23-24: 'Let him who boasts boast in knowing me' — Paul cites this in 1 Cor 1:31
  and 2 Cor 10:17; knowledge of God is now mediated through Christ (John 14:9).
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

JER_CHRIST = {
  "7": {
    "1": "<p>The heading of the Temple Sermon establishes it as a direct divine communication: <em>asher hayah el-Yirmiyahu me-et YHWH</em>. This prophetic authority pattern is the same structure Jesus claims: &apos;You have heard it was said ... but I say to you&apos; (Matt 5:21-48) — the direct divine voice that supersedes scribal transmission. Jesus&apos;s temple actions in the final week are the enacted fulfillment of this sermon.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Standing at the gate of the LORD&apos;s house to address those entering: Jesus&apos;s temple teaching also takes place in the temple courts (Matt 21-25; Mark 12; Luke 20-21). The audience is those entering to worship — those who assume that presence at the temple means covenant standing. Jesus also addresses the assumption that cultic proximity guarantees covenant security.</p>",
    "3": "<p>&apos;Reform your ways and your actions and I will let you live in this place&apos; — the conditional covenant of habitation. Jesus fulfills the unconditioned side of this covenant through his perfect obedience: he is the one who dwells with the Father without condition (John 1:1-2, 18), and through him the conditional requirement is met for those who are united with him (2 Cor 5:21). His death at Passover in Jerusalem is the ultimate reformed act that satisfies what Jeremiah&apos;s audience refused.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&apos;Do not trust in these deceptive words: the temple of the LORD, the temple of the LORD, the temple of the LORD.&apos; The triple chant is religious formula emptied of reality — the building invoked but the covenant ignored. Jesus will identify himself as the true temple (John 2:21) and declare that this building will be destroyed (Matt 24:2). The deceptive confidence in the structure rather than in YHWH is exactly what Jesus dismantles.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The conditions: truly reform, administer justice, do not exploit the foreigner, fatherless, widow. The legal-social content of genuine worship. Jesus in Matt 23:23 condemns those who tithe but &apos;neglect the weightier matters of the law: justice, mercy, and faithfulness.&apos; Both Jeremiah&apos;s Temple Sermon and Jesus&apos;s temple teaching identify the same failure: ritual compliance without covenantal justice.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Specific prohibitions: exploitation of the vulnerable, shedding innocent blood, following other gods. The shedding of innocent blood (<em>dam naqi</em>) points toward the ultimate innocent — Jesus, in whose death the long history of shedding innocent blood reaches its climax and its redemptive turning point. The disciples will later recall this context: &apos;I have sinned by betraying innocent blood&apos; (Matt 27:4 — Judas using the exact phrase).</p>",
    "7": "<p>The land-promise: obedience leads to dwelling in the land given to the ancestors. Jesus reframes the land-promise eschatologically: &apos;the meek will inherit the earth&apos; (Matt 5:5 = Ps 37:11); &apos;in my Father&apos;s house are many rooms ... I go to prepare a place for you&apos; (John 14:2). The promised dwelling that Judah forfeits through disobedience is restored through Christ&apos;s obedience — but expanded: not a geographic territory but the new creation.</p>",
    "8": "<p>&apos;You are trusting in deceptive words that can do you no good.&apos; The <em>davar sheqer</em> (deceptive/lying word) — the false security of temple-formula. Jesus warns against the same false security: &apos;not everyone who says to me Lord, Lord will enter the kingdom of heaven&apos; (Matt 7:21); &apos;you are like whitewashed tombs&apos; (Matt 23:27). Both Jeremiah and Jesus unmask the gap between religious performance and covenant reality.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The indictment catalog: steal, murder, commit adultery, swear falsely, sacrifice to Baal, follow other gods — and then come stand before YHWH in the temple. The Ten Commandments inverted: the worshippers break the covenant decalogue and then seek covenant blessing. Jesus&apos;s Sermon on the Mount (Matt 5-7) internalizes the same commandments: &apos;you have heard it said you shall not murder, but I say to you everyone who is angry...&apos; — reaching beneath the external act to the heart.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&apos;Come and stand before me in this house that bears my name and say: we are safe.&apos; The performative &apos;we are safe&apos; (<em>nittzalnu</em>) — ritual declaration of covenant standing. Jesus is the one in whose name all future prayer and covenant access is made (John 14:13-14; 16:23-24). His name replaces the temple as the locus of covenant presence.</p>",
    "11": "<p>&apos;Has this house, which bears my name, become a den of robbers in your eyes?&apos; — Jesus quotes this verse exactly (Mark 11:17: <em>spēlaion lēstōn</em> = den of robbers) when he drives out the temple traders. This is the most explicit NT citation of the Temple Sermon. Jesus applies Jeremiah&apos;s judgment speech to his own contemporaries, claiming prophetic continuity: what Jeremiah charged Jerusalem with in 609 BCE, Jesus charges with again in 30 CE. The temple has become what Jeremiah warned it would become.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&apos;Go to Shiloh ... see what I did to it.&apos; The Shiloh precedent: YHWH destroyed the first sanctuary when it was corrupted. Jesus&apos;s Olivet Discourse (Matt 24:1-2) gives the Jerusalem-temple equivalent: &apos;not one stone here will be left on another.&apos; The destruction of 70 CE is the fulfillment of the Shiloh-pattern warning renewed by Jesus, who renewed Jeremiah&apos;s renewal of the same warning.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&apos;I spoke to you again and again, but you did not listen&apos; — the persistent speaking (<em>hashkem vedabber</em>). Jesus identifies himself as the one in whom this persistent divine speech reaches its climax: &apos;in these last days he has spoken to us by his Son&apos; (Heb 1:2). The Son is the final, definitive word after the long sequence of servants.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The destruction of the temple because of its misuse. Fulfilled in 586 BCE; renewed as warning by Jesus (Matt 24:2); fulfilled again in 70 CE. The theological logic: the temple exists to mediate YHWH&apos;s presence; when it becomes an obstacle to that presence (substituting ritual for relationship), it is destroyed. Jesus&apos;s body becomes the new temple (John 2:21) — the dwelling of divine presence that cannot be permanently destroyed (John 2:19: &apos;I will raise it in three days&apos;).</p>",
    "15": "<p>The expulsion from divine presence — just as YHWH drove out the offspring of Ephraim. The exile from the land is the covenant curse of the Most Terrible: exclusion from YHWH&apos;s presence (Lev 26:33; Deut 28:36-37). Jesus&apos;s atonement is the reversal of this expulsion: &apos;I go to prepare a place for you ... that where I am you may also be&apos; (John 14:2-3). His crucifixion — the moment of maximum separation from the Father (&apos;My God, my God, why have you forsaken me&apos;) — is the bearing of this expulsion so that believers are never expelled.</p>",
    "16": "<p>&apos;Do not pray for this people.&apos; The prophetic intercession ban — the point of no return where judgment becomes fixed. Jesus, by contrast, prays for his people even at the point of maximum sin: &apos;Father, forgive them, for they do not know what they are doing&apos; (Luke 23:34). He is the intercessor who continues to plead beyond the point where human intercession fails (Heb 7:25: &apos;he always lives to make intercession for them&apos;).</p>",
    "17": "<p>YHWH directs Jeremiah to observe what the people are doing in the towns and streets. The omniscient divine attention to human behavior: &apos;Does he not see my ways and count my every step?&apos; (Job 31:4). Jesus&apos;s omniscient observation is consistent: he &apos;knew all people and needed no one to testify about man, for he himself knew what was in man&apos; (John 2:24-25).</p>",
    "18": "<p>The queen of heaven cult — the whole family participating in idolatry together: children gathering wood, fathers lighting the fire, women kneading dough. The comprehensive family participation in false worship is the opposite of the Shema&apos;s requirement to teach the commands to your children (Deut 6:6-9). Jesus comes to &apos;bring not peace but a sword&apos; (Matt 10:34-36) — family division over allegiance to him — because idolatrous family systems must be disrupted for covenant faithfulness.</p>",
    "19": "<p>&apos;Is it really me they are provoking? ... Is it not themselves they are harming?&apos; The logic of self-destructive sin: idolatry destroys the idolater, not YHWH. Jesus&apos;s teaching on sin follows the same logic: &apos;what comes out of a person is what defiles him&apos; (Mark 7:20-23). Sin is self-contaminating, not God-insulting in any sense that threatens God; the harm is to the sinner.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The wrath poured out on the land — on human, animal, and tree alike. Creation suffers under human sin: Rom 8:19-22 (the creation groaning, subjected to futility because of human failure). Jesus&apos;s death and resurrection initiates the re-creation that undoes this comprehensive curse: &apos;the creation itself will be liberated from its bondage to decay&apos; (Rom 8:21).</p>",
    "21": "<p>YHWH&apos;s satirical invitation to add burnt offerings to sacrifices and eat the meat: when the covenant relationship is broken, sacrifices become meaningless dietary exercises. Jesus fulfills and supersedes the entire sacrificial system: &apos;I desire mercy and not sacrifice&apos; (Matt 9:13; 12:7 quoting Hos 6:6), and his single offering perfects what the multiplied offerings could not (Heb 10:1-14).</p>",
    "22": "<p>&apos;On the day I brought your ancestors out of Egypt, I did not command them about burnt offerings and sacrifices.&apos; The Exodus-covenant priority: relationship and obedience precede sacrifice. Hebrews 10:5-7 quotes Ps 40:6-8 to make the same point about Jesus: &apos;sacrifice and offering you did not desire ... then I said, here I am, I have come to do your will.&apos; Jesus fulfills the original intention of the Sinai covenant by offering the obedience that the whole sacrificial system was pointing toward.</p>",
    "23": "<p>&apos;Obey me and I will be your God and you will be my people&apos; — the covenant formula in its simplest form. Jesus is the obedient one who perfectly fulfills the &apos;obey me&apos; side: &apos;not my will but yours be done&apos; (Luke 22:42); &apos;I always do the things that please him&apos; (John 8:29). His perfect obedience enacts the covenant formula on behalf of all who are in him; they become YHWH&apos;s people through his covenant-keeping.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The stubborn, evil hearts following their own plans — <em>shreruyt libbam hara</em> (the stubbornness of their evil hearts). Jesus diagnoses the same: &apos;from within, from the heart of man, come evil thoughts&apos; (Mark 7:21). His new covenant promise (31:33-34) is the answer: &apos;I will put my law in their minds and write it on their hearts.&apos; The new heart is the solution to the stubborn heart, accomplished through the Spirit poured out at Pentecost (Acts 2; Rom 8:3-4).</p>",
    "25": "<p>&apos;From the day your ancestors came out of Egypt until this very day, I have persistently sent all my servants the prophets.&apos; The servant-prophet pattern. The Parable of the Tenants (Matt 21:33-46) uses this exact sequence: servants sent to the vineyard → rejected → finally the son → killed. Jesus identifies himself as both the final prophet and the Son who is the climax of the whole sequence. Stephen&apos;s speech in Acts 7:51-52 makes the same identification: &apos;which of the prophets did your ancestors not persecute?... and now they have betrayed and murdered the Righteous One.&apos;</p>",
    "26": "<p>Each generation worse than the previous in not listening — the progressive hardening of Israel. Jesus observes the same: &apos;the sins of the fathers&apos; accumulating, the &apos;blood of all the prophets shed since the foundation of the world&apos; coming upon &apos;this generation&apos; (Luke 11:50-51; Matt 23:35-36). The cross is where the accumulated rejection reaches its apex — and where it is absorbed rather than returned.</p>",
    "27": "<p>&apos;You will speak all these words but they will not listen; you will call but they will not respond.&apos; The prophetic hardening oracle — given in advance so the prophet is not surprised by rejection. Jesus prepares his disciples for the same reception: &apos;if they persecuted me they will persecute you&apos; (John 15:20); &apos;a servant is not greater than his master&apos; (John 13:16). Rejection of the prophetic word is rejection of the sender.</p>",
    "28": "<p>&apos;This is the nation that did not obey the LORD their God and refused correction; faithfulness has perished, it has vanished from their lips.&apos; The funeral announcement of faithfulness. Jesus comes as the faithful witness (<em>ho martus ho pistos</em>, Rev 1:5; 3:14) — the one in whom faithfulness has not perished. He is the faithful Israelite where Israel was unfaithful, making him the representative who can absorb the judgment and restore the relationship.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The shaving and lamenting on the hilltops — mourning rites for the LORD&apos;s rejection and abandonment of his generation. Jesus&apos;s lament over Jerusalem (Matt 23:37-39; Luke 19:41-44) takes up this same mourning: he weeps over the city whose generation has become the rejected generation of Jeremiah&apos;s vision. &apos;O Jerusalem, Jerusalem, you who kill the prophets ... your house is left to you desolate.&apos;</p>",
    "30": "<p>Detestable idols in the house bearing YHWH&apos;s name — the temple defiled. Jesus enters the temple and drives out those who have made it a marketplace: &apos;my house shall be called a house of prayer for all nations&apos; (Mark 11:17). He reclaims the holiness of YHWH&apos;s name-space. His own body is the holy temple (John 2:21) that replaces the defiled one.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Topheth in the Valley of Ben Hinnom — child sacrifice to Molech, called &apos;the thing I did not command and that never entered my mind.&apos; This valley (<em>Gei Hinnom</em> in Hebrew, <em>Gehenna</em> in Greek) becomes the NT&apos;s primary image of final judgment. Jesus uses <em>Gehenna</em> twelve times in the Gospels (Matt 5:22, 29-30; 10:28; 18:9; 23:15, 33; Mark 9:43-47; Luke 12:5) as the place of judgment — the place where fire consumed the defilements of the city. The valley&apos;s history of child sacrifice and later of burning the city&apos;s refuse gives Jesus&apos;s imagery its force.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The renaming: Topheth and the Valley of Ben Hinnom become the Valley of Slaughter because of the mass burial needed. The irony: the place where Israel sacrificed children to Molech becomes the mass grave of the Israeli dead. The NT&apos;s Gehenna incorporates this irony: the judgment image derives from the very place of Israel&apos;s worst sin. Jesus warns that the final judgment is more terrible than any earthly slaughter — the fire that never goes out (Mark 9:43-48).</p>",
    "33": "<p>Corpses as food for birds and beasts, with no one to frighten them away — the maximum desecration, the covenant curse of Deut 28:26. Jesus takes this curse in his own death: crucified outside the city, exposed (Col 2:15; Gal 3:13: &apos;cursed is everyone who is hung on a tree&apos;). But his body is given an honorable burial (John 19:38-42) and raised — the reversal of the curse that those he represents deserved.</p>",
    "34": "<p>&apos;I will silence the voices of the bridegroom and bride.&apos; The judgment-silencing of covenant joy. Jesus identifies himself as the bridegroom (John 3:29; Matt 9:15; 25:1-13). His presence marks the return of wedding joy: &apos;while the bridegroom is with them, they cannot fast&apos; (Mark 2:19). The silence of Jer 7:34 is what his arrival reverses; Rev 19:7 announces the final restoration of this joy: &apos;Let us rejoice and be glad and give him glory, for the wedding of the Lamb has come.&apos;</p>"
  },
  "8": {
    "1": "<p>The bones of the kings, priests, prophets, and inhabitants exposed — the judgment on the entire leadership and people of Judah. The exposure of bones (rather than burial) is the ultimate covenant-curse degradation. Jesus specifically protects even dead bodies: in John 19:31-37 the soldiers do not break his legs (fulfilling Ps 34:20: &apos;not one of his bones will be broken&apos;) — and he is buried with honor before the Sabbath. His resurrection is the first-fruits of the bodily restoration that reverses the bone-exposure judgment.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Bones spread before the sun, moon, and stars they worshiped — the divine irony: they loved and served the heavenly bodies, now their bones will be exposed to those same bodies as carrion. Jesus is the light that exceeds the sun, moon, and stars (Rev 21:23: &apos;the city does not need the sun or the moon to shine on it, for the glory of God gives it light, and the Lamb is its lamp&apos;). Worship directed to creation objects rather than the Creator is corrected in him.</p>",
    "3": "<p>&apos;Survivors of this evil family ... will prefer death to life.&apos; The complete reversal of covenant blessing: instead of &apos;choosing life&apos; (Deut 30:19), the judgment-generation prefers death. Jesus comes specifically to reverse this death-preference: &apos;I have come that they may have life, and have it to the full&apos; (John 10:10). His resurrection is the proof that the preference for life is vindicated by God himself.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&apos;When people fall, don&apos;t they get back up? When someone turns away, don&apos;t they return?&apos; The natural human reflex — fall, get up; stray, return — is inexplicably absent in Israel. Jesus is the one who enables the return: &apos;I am the way&apos; (John 14:6); the good shepherd leaves the ninety-nine to seek the one who has strayed (Luke 15:4-7). He restores the capacity for return that Israel&apos;s stubbornness has disabled.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Perpetual backsliding — clinging to deception and refusing to return. <em>Meshuvah netzachat</em> (perpetual backsliding): the chronic, unreformable condition. Jesus addresses this with the new covenant promise: &apos;I will give you a new heart and put a new spirit in you; I will remove the heart of stone and give you a heart of flesh&apos; (Ezek 36:26) — the cure for perpetual backsliding is heart-replacement, accomplished through the Spirit that Jesus gives (John 7:37-39; Acts 2:33).</p>",
    "6": "<p>&apos;No one repents of his wickedness and asks: What have I done?&apos; The absent repentance. Jesus&apos;s ministry begins and centers on the call to repentance: <em>metanoeite</em> (repent!) is his opening word (Matt 4:17; Mark 1:15). His parables of the lost sheep, lost coin, and prodigal son (Luke 15) celebrate the repentance that Jeremiah found absent. He enables what Jeremiah could not find — genuine return to the Father.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&apos;The stork knows when to migrate... but my people do not know the ordinances of the LORD.&apos; Animals follow their instincts given by the Creator; Israel has lost its covenant instinct. Jesus fulfills the covenant ordinances perfectly (Matt 5:17: &apos;I have not come to abolish the Law but to fulfill it&apos;) and rebukes his contemporaries for not reading &apos;the signs of the times&apos; as birds read seasonal signs (Matt 16:3; Luke 12:56): they have lost the ability to discern what is right before them.</p>",
    "8": "<p>&apos;We are wise and have the law of the LORD — but the lying pen of scribes has made it a lie.&apos; Scribal distortion of the divine word. Jesus&apos;s repeated &apos;You have heard it said ... but I say to you&apos; (Matt 5:21-48) addresses this directly: he cuts through the scribal accretion to YHWH&apos;s original intention. John 1:1, 14: the Logos who was with God from the beginning and became flesh is the authoritative interpreter who cannot be corrupted — the divine word unmediated through fallible scribes.</p>",
    "9": "<p>&apos;The wise will be disgraced... they rejected the word of the LORD — what wisdom do they have?&apos; Paul&apos;s theology of the cross engages precisely this verse: &apos;where is the wise man? Where is the scholar? ... has not God made foolish the wisdom of the world?&apos; (1 Cor 1:20). The wisdom that rejects the divine word — whether Jeremiah&apos;s word or the cross — is self-refuting. Christ crucified is &apos;the power of God and the wisdom of God&apos; (1 Cor 1:24) that exposes all other wisdom as insufficient.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Wives given to others, fields to new owners — the covenant curse of economic dispossession (Deut 28:30). The prophets from least to greatest practice deception; priests teach for profit. Jesus similarly indicts the religious leadership of his day: &apos;everything they do is done for people to see&apos; (Matt 23:5); the scribes who &apos;devour widows&apos; houses&apos; (Mark 12:40). The leadership failure of Jeremiah&apos;s priests and prophets is the same failure Jesus confronts in the temple establishment.</p>",
    "11": "<p>&apos;They dress the wound of my people as though it were minor, saying: peace, peace, when there is no peace.&apos; The false comfort of superficial healing — <em>shalom shalom ve-ein shalom</em>. Jesus refuses superficial comfort and names the real condition: &apos;I have not come to bring peace but a sword&apos; (Matt 10:34) — not endorsing violence but refusing the false peace that avoids the real diagnosis. His peace is different: &apos;peace I leave with you; my peace I give to you. Not as the world gives do I give to you&apos; (John 14:27) — the authentic shalom that comes through dealing honestly with sin.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&apos;Were they ashamed? No, they felt no shame; they did not even know how to blush.&apos; The loss of moral sensibility — <em>lehikkalam lo yeda-u</em>. Jesus identifies the same condition in Pharisees who are confident of their righteousness while actually being blind (John 9:39-41: &apos;for judgment I came into this world, so that the blind will see and those who see will become blind&apos;). The shame-insensitive are not those who obviously sin but those who perform righteousness with pride; genuine shame before God is the beginning of repentance.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&apos;I will take away their harvest ... no grapes on the vine, no figs on the fig tree.&apos; The agricultural curse: the productive covenant land becomes barren. Jesus enacts this judgment symbolically in the cursing of the fig tree (Matt 21:18-22; Mark 11:12-14, 20-25) — the fig tree with leaves but no fruit represents Israel with religious form but no covenant reality. The withered tree is the enacted sign of what the temple represents.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The people&apos;s own despairing call to flee to fortified cities and die there — YHWH has given them poison to drink. The self-awareness of being under divine judgment: &apos;we have sinned against the LORD.&apos; This admission of sin without return is the condition that Jesus comes to cure: he makes genuine repentance possible by taking the poison cup himself (&apos;let this cup pass from me — yet not my will but yours&apos;, Matt 26:39) so that those who confess sin find mercy rather than death.</p>",
    "15": "<p>&apos;We hoped for peace, but no good has come; we waited for healing, but instead there is terror.&apos; The exhausted, desolate waiting for shalom that never arrives. Jesus is the answer to this waiting: &apos;the kingdom of God has come near&apos; (Mark 1:15) announces the arrival of the shalom that this verse says never came. His Beatitudes (Matt 5:3-12) describe those who were waiting in exactly this posture: &apos;blessed are those who hunger and thirst for righteousness, for they will be filled.&apos;</p>",
    "16": "<p>The northern invader — snorting warhorses heard from Dan, the whole land trembling. The terrifying invasion that the people feared and the prophets announced. Jesus&apos;s eschatological discourse (Matt 24; Luke 21) describes the coming of judgment in terms that echo these invasion oracles: &apos;when you see these things happening, you know that the kingdom of God is near.&apos; The historical judgment on Jerusalem (70 CE) fulfills this pattern within the generation of Jesus&apos;s hearers (Matt 24:34).</p>",
    "17": "<p>&apos;I am sending poisonous snakes among you — vipers that cannot be charmed — and they will bite you.&apos; The snake imagery of judgment. Jesus uses snake imagery for his opponents: &apos;you brood of vipers&apos; (Matt 3:7; 12:34; 23:33); but he also takes up the snake-image for himself: &apos;as Moses lifted up the snake in the wilderness, so must the Son of Man be lifted up, that everyone who believes may have eternal life in him&apos; (John 3:14-15). He takes on the judgment-form to become the healing-form: the snake of judgment becomes the snake of salvation on the pole.</p>",
    "18": "<p>&apos;My sorrow is beyond healing; my heart is faint within me.&apos; Jeremiah&apos;s personal grief — the prophet sharing YHWH&apos;s own heartbreak. Jesus weeps over Jerusalem (Luke 19:41) and expresses the divine sorrow: &apos;how often I have longed to gather your children together, as a hen gathers her chicks under her wings, and you were not willing&apos; (Matt 23:37). The prophet&apos;s grief in ch. 8-9 is the prototype of the Son&apos;s grief over the same city — the same people, centuries later, in the same spiritual condition.</p>",
    "19": "<p>&apos;Is the LORD not in Zion? Is her King no longer there?&apos; The desperate cry from exile wondering whether YHWH has abandoned his people. Jesus is the answer — the LORD who came to Zion in person (John 1:14: the Word <em>eskēnōsen</em>, tabernacled, among us; Matt 1:23: Emmanuel, God with us). The cry &apos;Is the LORD not in Zion?&apos; is answered by the incarnation: yes, YHWH is in Zion — in the person of Jesus of Nazareth.</p>",
    "20": "<p>&apos;The harvest is over, the summer has ended — and we are still not saved.&apos; The most despairing verse of the chapter: all the natural seasons of opportunity have passed; salvation has not come. Jesus announces the reversal of this despair: the kingdom of God is the harvest finally arriving (Matt 9:37-38: &apos;the harvest is plentiful but the workers are few&apos;); he is the one who saves — <em>Yeshua</em>, whose name means YHWH saves. The summer is not over; the harvest has begun.</p>",
    "21": "<p>&apos;I am broken over the brokenness of my people; I mourn, and horror has gripped me.&apos; The prophet&apos;s shared suffering with his people — he carries their pain. This is the prophet-as-intercessor pattern that anticipates Christ&apos;s high-priestly role: &apos;he is able to deal gently with those who are ignorant and are going astray, since he himself is subject to weakness&apos; (Heb 5:2); &apos;we do not have a high priest who is unable to empathize with our weaknesses&apos; (Heb 4:15). The broken prophet is the type of the broken priest-king who bears the people&apos;s brokenness himself.</p>",
    "22": "<p>&apos;Is there no balm in Gilead? Is there no physician there? Then why has the wound of my people not been healed?&apos; — the most celebrated lament in Jeremiah, encapsulating the whole chapter&apos;s anguish. The <em>tzori</em> (balm) of Gilead (the aromatic resin-based healing substance from the Gilead region, cf. Gen 37:25; Jer 46:11) was the best medicinal treatment available. But no balm heals; no physician restores. Jesus comes as the divine physician: &apos;those who are well have no need of a physician, but those who are sick do; I have not come to call the righteous but sinners&apos; (Matt 9:12-13; Mark 2:17). He is the balm of Gilead; he is the physician. The unanswerable lament of 8:22 is answered by the incarnation.</p>"
  },
  "9": {
    "1": "<p>&apos;Oh that my head were a spring of water and my eyes a fountain of tears, so that I could weep day and night for the slain of my people!&apos; Jeremiah&apos;s tears are a prophetic type of Christ&apos;s tears. Jesus weeps over Jerusalem (Luke 19:41: <em>eklausen ep&apos; autēn</em>, he wept over it) with the same combination of prophetic grief and divine anguish. John 11:35 (&apos;Jesus wept&apos;) — the shortest verse in the NT — shows the same tear-fountain at the death of Lazarus. The weeping prophet is fulfilled in the weeping Son: YHWH&apos;s grief for his people becomes incarnate grief.</p>",
    "2": "<p>&apos;Oh that I had a lodging place in the wilderness, so that I could leave my people and go away — for they are all adulterers, a crowd of treacherous people!&apos; The prophet&apos;s exhausted longing for escape from a faithless people. Jesus never expresses this longing — he goes through the temptation to withdraw (Gethsemane) but chooses to stay and drink the cup. Where Jeremiah longed to leave, Christ chose to remain: &apos;I will not leave you as orphans; I will come to you&apos; (John 14:18). His determination to remain with his people fulfills what the prophet yearned to abandon.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The tongue as a bow shooting falsehood (<em>yidreku et-leshonam qeshtam sheqer</em>). The community of deceit — powerful in the land but not by truth. James 3:2-12 elaborates the tongue-as-weapon image: the tongue is &apos;a fire, a world of evil among the parts of the body.&apos; Jesus addresses the tongue-and-truth issue directly: &apos;let your yes be yes and your no be no; anything more comes from the evil one&apos; (Matt 5:37). He himself is the Truth (John 14:6) — the counterpart of the land of deceit.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&apos;Every brother is a schemer&apos; (<em>kol-ach aqov ya-aqov</em> — playing on &apos;Jacob&apos;, the heel-grabber/schemer). The universal distrust within the covenant community. Jesus enters this community of treachery and is himself betrayed by a close companion (John 13:18; Ps 41:9 — &apos;even my close friend who shared my bread has lifted his heel against me&apos;). He knows the Jacob-pattern from inside human experience — and his self-giving into betrayal reverses the pattern: the one who could have deceived chose radical transparency.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Universal deception, tongues trained to lie, exhausted by iniquity. Jesus&apos;s testimony: &apos;I have spoken openly to the world; I always taught in synagogues or at the temple... I said nothing in secret&apos; (John 18:20). He is the anti-type of the deceptive tongue: total transparency, full disclosure, the word that cannot be falsified. In him the community of trained liars encounters the one who cannot lie (Titus 1:2: &apos;God, who does not lie&apos;).</p>",
    "6": "<p>&apos;You live in the midst of deception; through their deceit they refuse to know me, declares the LORD.&apos; The knowledge-of-God failure at the root of all the deception. Jesus is the definitive revelation of the Father: &apos;Anyone who has seen me has seen the Father&apos; (John 14:9); &apos;No one knows the Father except the Son and those to whom the Son chooses to reveal him&apos; (Matt 11:27). Refusing to know Jesus is refusing to know the LORD — the same refusal Jeremiah identifies as the community&apos;s core failure.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&apos;I will refine them and test them — for what else can I do with my people?&apos; The divine refining through judgment — the only remaining option when all other means of restoration have failed. Jesus himself is the refiner: &apos;he will baptize you with the Holy Spirit and fire&apos; (Matt 3:11-12); &apos;his winnowing fork is in his hand&apos; (Matt 3:12). The refinement through the cross — bearing the judgment fire himself — is the ultimate form of YHWH&apos;s refining of his people.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The tongue as lethal arrow, speaking peace with the mouth while ambushing in the heart. Judas&apos;s betrayal kiss (Matt 26:49: &apos;Greetings, Rabbi!&apos; — peace-speech with a treacherous purpose) is the exact fulfillment of this pattern. The one who kisses Jesus to betray him enacts the &apos;peace in the mouth, ambush in the heart&apos; dynamic of 9:8. Jesus receives the ambush in the mouth and bears it without retaliating in kind.</p>",
    "9": "<p>&apos;Should I not punish them? Should I not take vengeance on such a nation?&apos; The divine justice that demands accountability. Jesus takes the full weight of this divine vengeance in his own person on the cross: &apos;Christ redeemed us from the curse of the law by becoming a curse for us&apos; (Gal 3:13). The vengeance YHWH takes on the faithless nation is absorbed by the faithful Son — so that the nation does not bear it, but lives through his bearing.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Weeping and wailing for the mountains, lament for the wilderness pastures: the land is desolate because everyone has left. Jesus&apos;s lament over the cities of Galilee (Matt 11:20-24: &apos;woe to you, Chorazin! Woe to you, Bethsaida!&apos;) uses the same lament-over-land pattern: the city that rejected his ministry will be more desolate than Sodom and Gomorrah. The land suffers when YHWH&apos;s word is rejected.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Jerusalem a heap of rubble, a haunt of jackals; cities of Judah desolate. Fulfilled in 70 CE — the destruction of Jerusalem that Jesus announced (Matt 24:2; Luke 21:20-24: &apos;let those in Judea flee to the mountains...&apos;). The jackals-in-Jerusalem image that Jeremiah saw in vision, Jesus sees approaching and announces as imminent. The gap between Jeremiah&apos;s oracle and the destruction of Jerusalem mirrors the gap between Jesus&apos;s oracle and 70 CE.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&apos;Who is wise enough to understand this? Who has received the word from the LORD and can explain it?&apos; The call for an interpreter of disaster. Jesus is the ultimate interpreter of the divine purpose in judgment: he explains to the disciples on the Emmaus road &apos;everything in the Scriptures concerning himself&apos; (Luke 24:27), including why it was necessary for the Messiah to suffer. He has received the word from the LORD — &apos;my teaching is not my own; it comes from the one who sent me&apos; (John 7:16).</p>",
    "13": "<p>The LORD&apos;s explanation: they abandoned my law (<em>torati</em>) that I placed before them, did not obey, and did not walk in it. Jesus frames his own teaching as the internalized Torah: &apos;I will put my laws in their minds and write them on their hearts&apos; (Heb 8:10 quoting Jer 31:33). The external Torah abandoned by Jeremiah&apos;s generation becomes the internal Torah inscribed by the Spirit — the new covenant solution to the old covenant failure.</p>",
    "14": "<p>They followed the stubbornness of their hearts and went after the Baals as their ancestors taught them. The intergenerational transmission of idolatry — taught apostasy rather than taught Torah (cf. Deut 6:7). Jesus teaches his disciples to make new disciples and teach them (Matt 28:19-20) — the intergenerational transmission of covenant faithfulness that reverses the intergenerational transmission of Baal worship.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Wormwood and poisoned water fed to the people because of apostasy. The bitter waters of judgment. Revelation 8:10-11 uses the wormwood image for the end-time judgment: &apos;a great star ... fell on a third of the rivers ... the name of the star is Wormwood.&apos; Jesus, at the cross, is offered wine mixed with gall (Matt 27:34) — the bitter draught, which he initially refuses — then drinks the full cup of suffering (v. 42: &apos;let him come down from the cross&apos;). He drinks the wormwood so the covenant people do not have to drink it permanently.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Scattered among nations, pursued by the sword until consumed. The comprehensive exile. Jesus&apos;s own flight to Egypt as an infant (Matt 2:13-15) makes him a participant in the diaspora pattern — &apos;out of Egypt I called my son&apos; (Hos 11:1, quoted in Matt 2:15). He is the true Israel in exile who returns; his resurrection is the return from the ultimate &apos;exile&apos; of death.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Summon the mourning women — the professional lament-singers. The organized mourning liturgy of the ancient Near East: trained women who led communal grief. Jesus encounters such mourning in the NT: at Jairus&apos;s daughter (Mark 5:38-39: &apos;people crying and wailing loudly&apos;) and at Lazarus&apos;s tomb (John 11:31-33). In both cases he transforms mourning into resurrection hope: &apos;she is not dead but sleeping&apos; (Mark 5:39); &apos;your brother will rise again&apos; (John 11:23). The mourning-women tradition is not abolished but superseded.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Tears streaming from eyes, eyelids overflowing with water — the lament that YHWH calls for. Jesus in Gethsemane: &apos;being in anguish, he prayed more earnestly, and his sweat was like drops of blood falling to the ground&apos; (Luke 22:44) — the physical intensity of his grief prefigures the weeping and tears that Heb 5:7 attributes to him: &apos;during the days of Jesus&apos;s life on earth, he offered up prayers and petitions with fervent cries and tears.&apos; The weeping of 9:18 has its NT fulfillment in the Son&apos;s tears.</p>",
    "19": "<p>&apos;We are devastated! We are utterly disgraced — because we have had to leave the land and our houses have been torn down.&apos; The exile&apos;s lament — loss of land and dwelling as the expression of covenant loss. Jesus promises a dwelling that no exile can take away: &apos;in my Father&apos;s house are many rooms ... I am going to prepare a place for you&apos; (John 14:2). The permanence of the dwelling he prepares reverses the impermanence of the houses torn down in exile.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Women commanded to hear the word of the LORD — teach your daughters to mourn; teach one another the lament. The female transmission of grief. The women at the cross (Luke 23:27-31) enact this: Jesus addresses them directly: &apos;daughters of Jerusalem, do not weep for me; weep for yourselves and for your children.&apos; He directs their grief toward the coming destruction of 70 CE — the lament-teaching that Jeremiah prescribes is here applied by Jesus to his own generation.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Death climbing through windows, entering palaces, cutting down children in the streets. The invasion of death into every space — no fortress sufficient. Jesus faces death in its full power and rises: &apos;Death has been swallowed up in victory. Where, O death, is your victory? Where, O death, is your sting?&apos; (1 Cor 15:54-55 citing Isa 25:8 and Hos 13:14). Death&apos;s climb through the windows of v. 21 is reversed by Christ&apos;s victory over death in the resurrection.</p>",
    "22": "<p>&apos;Human corpses will fall like manure on the open field, like grain stalks left behind the reaper, with no one to gather them.&apos; The exposed, ungathered dead of judgment. Jesus comes as the gatherer: &apos;the Son of Man will send out his angels and they will weed out of his kingdom everything that causes sin ... and gather his elect from the four winds&apos; (Matt 13:41; 24:31). The no-one-to-gather of 9:22 becomes the final gathering of the Son&apos;s harvest.</p>",
    "23": "<p>&apos;Let not the wise boast in their wisdom, nor the mighty in their strength, nor the rich in their riches.&apos; The threefold prohibition of self-boasting. Paul cites this as the foundation of his entire theology of the cross: &apos;it is because of him that you are in Christ Jesus, who has become for us wisdom from God — that is, our righteousness, holiness and redemption. Therefore, as it is written: &apos;Let him who boasts boast in the Lord&apos;&apos; (1 Cor 1:30-31). The wisdom, strength, and riches that cannot be boasted are redefined and concentrated in Christ crucified.</p>",
    "24": "<p>&apos;But let him who boasts boast in this: that he understands and knows me — that I am the LORD who exercises steadfast love, justice, and righteousness on earth, for in these I delight.&apos; To know YHWH as the one who does <em>chesed</em>, <em>mishpat</em>, and <em>tzedaqah</em> — and to boast only in that knowing. Jesus is the knowledge of God made accessible: &apos;anyone who has seen me has seen the Father&apos; (John 14:9); &apos;now this is eternal life: that they know you, the only true God, and Jesus Christ, whom you have sent&apos; (John 17:3). Boasting in knowing YHWH is now, in the NT, boasting in knowing Christ.</p>",
    "25": "<p>&apos;The days are coming when I will punish all who are only outwardly circumcised.&apos; The critique of outward-only circumcision. Paul elaborates this in Rom 2:28-29: &apos;a person is not a Jew who is one outwardly, nor is circumcision merely outward and physical; no, a person is a Jew who is one inwardly, and circumcision is circumcision of the heart, by the Spirit.&apos; Col 2:11-12 applies this to Christ: &apos;in him you were also circumcised with a circumcision not performed by human hands.&apos; Christ provides the true circumcision of the heart that Jeremiah and Deuteronomy (10:16; 30:6) required.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Egypt, Judah, Edom, Ammon, Moab, and the clipped-haired Arabs — all circumcised in flesh but uncircumcised in heart. The comprehensive list of the outwardly-circumcised but inwardly-uncircumcised dismantles any ethnic pride in covenant signs. Paul in Galatians and Romans makes the same argument globally: circumcision neither confers righteousness nor does its absence disqualify from covenant standing (Gal 5:6: &apos;neither circumcision nor uncircumcision has any value; the only thing that counts is faith expressing itself through love&apos;). The true Israel is defined by the heart-circumcision that Christ provides.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'jeremiah')
    merge_comm(existing, JER_CHRIST)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'jeremiah', existing)

    out = json.loads((ROOT / 'data/commentary/mkt-christ/jeremiah.json').read_text())
    il  = json.loads((ROOT / 'data/interlinear/jeremiah.json').read_text())

    all_ok = True
    for ch in [7, 8, 9]:
        ck = str(ch)
        missing = set(il.get(ck, {}).keys()) - set(out.get(ck, {}).keys())
        if missing:
            print(f'ch {ch} STILL MISSING: {sorted(missing, key=int)}')
            all_ok = False
        else:
            print(f'ch {ch}: complete ({len(out.get(ck, {}))} verses)')
    if all_ok:
        print('All verses present')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
